 to violent acts of mutiny in which lascar crews murdered officers, seized ships and then sought refuge with local rulers. It is only through descriptions of such events - found in logbooks, seafaring diaries and the East India Company's judicial records - that many aspects of lascar life at sea become visible and lascar voices can be heard. Through the study of mutiny and other forms of protest, the book provides a detailed insight into shipboard conditions amongst lascars employed during this period. Aaron Jaffer completed his doctorate in history at the University of Warwick.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArthurian romancesxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish literatureyMiddle English, 1100-1500xHistory and criticism. 0aMutinyxHistoryy18th centuryzIndia. 0aMutinyxHistoryy19th centuryzIndia. 0aSailorsxHistoryy18th centuryzIndia. 0aSailorsxHistoryy19th centuryzIndia. 0aSeafaring lifexHistoryy18th centuryzIndia. 0aSeafaring lifexHistoryy19th centuryzIndia. 4aMaritime History. 4aModern History. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  aColonial History.  aCultural Diversity.  aIndian Ocean.  aIndian Subcontinent.  aLascars.  aMaritime History.  aMutiny.  aSeafaring.  aShipboard Life.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2015z978311143132140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781782045939?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782045939423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782045939/original  a978-3-11-143132-1  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2015b2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles